about something you mentioned

00:45:10.160 --> 00:45:12.740
also, which was who is the
other and that concept of trying

00:45:12.740 --> 00:45:18.920
to work past that abstract
notion of the other person,

00:45:18.920 --> 00:45:23.150
the other group, or the other
sort of ideology or philosophy.

00:45:23.150 --> 00:45:24.890
So I'm wondering
what kind of advice

00:45:24.890 --> 00:45:28.520
do you have regarding
any perceived

00:45:28.520 --> 00:45:32.810
divide or actual divide to
stay with it for Christians,

00:45:32.810 --> 00:45:35.210
for LGBTQ individuals.

00:45:35.210 --> 00:45:39.440
I mean, how to stay with it,
how to work past that doubt.

00:45:42.520 --> 00:45:45.730
NATHAN ALBERT: I
would say that to stay

00:45:45.730 --> 00:45:49.930
with it, what comes often
past the bend of stay

00:45:49.930 --> 00:45:52.780
with it can be
reconciliation, which

00:45:52.780 --> 00:45:54.930
is a really beautiful thing.

00:45:54.930 --> 00:45:58.660
And I see this best with
gay children and parents.

00:45:58.660 --> 00:46:02.260
And I often say to
many of my gay friends

00:46:02.260 --> 00:46:05.540
who when they come out to
their parents, what happens

00:46:05.540 --> 00:46:06.760
is a shift happens.

00:46:06.760 --> 00:46:09.135
Where they become-- and we
talked a little bit about this

00:46:09.135 --> 00:46:10.310
at lunch.

00:46:10.310 --> 00:46:12.490
Where they become the
parent and the parents

00:46:12.490 --> 00:46:13.900
act like little children.

00:46:13.900 --> 00:46:16.090
So it's like my son is gay?

00:46:16.090 --> 00:46:16.840
What?

00:46:16.840 --> 00:46:19.210
And they bang and they
pout and they stomp around,

00:46:19.210 --> 00:46:22.150
like they act like little
kids having a temper tantrum.

00:46:22.150 --> 00:46:24.950
And in that moment,
I always encourage

00:46:24.950 --> 00:46:27.790
that the child
becomes the parent,

00:46:27.790 --> 00:46:31.540
and has to parent that
parent through the process,

00:46:31.540 --> 00:46:33.480
through this process.

00:46:33.480 --> 00:46:37.930
And every time that
I've seen that happen,

00:46:37.930 --> 00:46:44.020
it has always ended in a
positive and good relationship.

00:46:44.020 --> 00:46:46.700
And now I think there are times
where ending relationships are

00:46:46.700 --> 00:46:47.200
important.

00:46:47.200 --> 00:46:50.390
Where they become abusive and
emotionally or spiritually,

00:46:50.390 --> 00:46:52.780
physically abusive,
there's no doubt about it

00:46:52.780 --> 00:46:55.540
that certain
relationships need to end.

00:46:55.540 --> 00:46:57.590
So I'm not saying that.

00:46:57.590 --> 00:47:02.460
But I think around that
bend comes a reconciliation

00:47:02.460 --> 00:47:05.950
and a type of relationship
that just is better

00:47:05.950 --> 00:47:07.390
than what it was even before.

00:47:07.390 --> 00:47:11.590
So I think that's
one of the glimpses

00:47:11.590 --> 00:47:14.650
of if you stay with it.

00:47:14.650 --> 00:47:17.920
And you know, the whole it
gets better campaign that

00:47:17.920 --> 00:47:20.050
